<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-956-144  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 956 144.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Dec 11 1989 v23 n50 p54(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Beating back a Basic bad rap. (sales figures of Basic products)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Simson, Charles von.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Basic computer language has a reputation for being powerless,but its popularity remains strong.andP;  About 62 percent of the marketis corporate developers, with most of the rest hobbyists or homeusers.andP;  Microsoft Corp owns at least 70 percent of the Basicmarket and expects to ship nearly 100,000 copies of the $99.95Quick Basic in 1990.andP;  In the first third of 1988, Quick Basicaccounted for 46 percent of the total Microsoft language sales toFortune 100 companies.andP;  Microsoft's strong position primarilyresults from the fact that Basic was the language of choice whencorporations began installing microcomputers.andP;  Microsoft isreleasing a $495 Basic compiler.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (sales statistics).andO;Product:   QuickBASIC (Compiler) (sales statistics).andO;Topic:     BASICUser StudiesCompilersProduct Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>